{"add":{"doc":{"id":"56d1b473b4058ee12a13238806d60753a92624e14baea6fb3cabb00eb572a544","url":"https://upload.wikimedia.org/wikipedia/commons/f/f1/Nabta.gif","previous":[],"after":["Nabta Playa at the southwest corner of the western Egyptian desert was once a large lake in the Nubian Desert, located 500 miles south of modern-day Cairo.[13] By the 5th millennium BC, the peoples in Nabta Playa had fashioned an astronomical device that accurately marks the summer solstice.[citation needed] Findings indicate that the region was occupied only seasonally, likely only in the summer when the local lake filled with water for grazing cattle.[14] There are other megalithic stone circles in the southwestern desert."]}}}